Introduction

The purpose of this notebook is to refactor the analysis completed previously by myself in Fall 2023 into a single pipeline in this markdown document. I will attempt to include all relevant communications, decisions, and references used to generate the information. The ultimate goal is that the document itself is a complete record of information used to generate the results, as well as the results themselves.

Hypotheses

H1.1 Sugars ~ Phenology

The higher energy that is available, the more sugars will be exuded and detected. See Analysis of H1.1.

H1.2 Starches ~ Phenology

Starches will be detected in late season (SENE) rather than during peaks. See Analysis of H1.2.

H1.3 TOC ~ Phenology

The higher energy that is available, the more C exudation will be detected. See Analysis of H1.3.

H2.1 Colonization \(\propto\) TOC

This analysis was dropped.

H3.1 Long Ratio ~ Phenology

Root tip contact type (long versus contact) depends on C availability. In a full-leaf state, we expect higher carbon availability, and a shift to long roots. See Analysis of H3.1.

The Data

Primary Data

The sample and control data are stored in two seperate csv files located in the data/raw/ folder. These tables need to be combined into a single data table for analysis, as well as calculating the control mean for each of the six sampling periods. For metadata on data table variables, see appendix S1: Variable Metadata.

Minor Cleaning

Adding a year column:

aspen <- aspen %>%
  mutate(year = paste0("Y",str_extract(date_id, "\\d{4}")), .after = "date_id")

Set factor levels for phenology to (LEAF, FULL, SENE) and set date_id as a factor:

aspen$phenology <- factor(aspen$phenology, levels = c("LEAF", "FULL", "SENE"))
aspen$date_id <- factor(aspen$date_id)

Derived Data

Standardized Total Organic Carbon

The existing c_conc variable is in mg/L, so this needs to be:

  1. Corrected by the sampling date group mean of the control blanks TOC concentration
  2. Standardized by the sample mass and flush volume.

The formula for our new mass fraction variable, exudate_ratio is then:

\[\text{exudate_ratio}=\frac{\text{(TOC_raw}-\text{control_TOC_mean)}*\text{sample_flush_vol}}{\text{fine_root_mass}}*\frac{1000 \mu g}{mg}\]

Applying this formula to the datatable:

aspen <- aspen %>%
  mutate(exudate_ratio = (TOC_raw - control_TOC_mean)*sample_flush_vol/fine_root_mass*1000)

All Sugars

all_sugars is defined as the sum of the concentrations of all fungal and tree sugars: fructose, arabitol, glucose, mannitol, sucrose, and trehalose. Units are \(\mu\text{g/mg}\).

aspen <- aspen %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(all_sugars = sum(c_across(fructose:trehalose)), .after="trehalose") %>% ungroup()

Root Tip Proportion Variables

All proportions are simply the variable / total_root_tips with the exceptions of: \[\text{contact_ratio}=\frac{\text{contact_p}}{\text{long_p}}\] \[\text{long_ratio}=\frac{\text{long_p}}{\text{colonized_p}}\]

aspen <- aspen %>%
  rename(colonized=colonized_root_tips) %>%
  mutate(colonized_p = colonized/total_root_tips,
         uncolonized_p = uncolonized/total_root_tips,
         contact_p = contact/total_root_tips,
         long_p = long/total_root_tips,
         contact_ratio = contact_p/colonized_p,
         long_ratio = long_p/colonized_p,
         .after = "total_root_tips")

Export and Archive

Archive the prepared data table in both .csv and .Rdata formats for future use. The RDS data file will be the canonical data table called by the getAspen() function for all future analysis.

write_csv(aspen, "data/processed/23ARE_datatable.csv")
saveRDS(aspen, "data/processed/23ARE_datatable.rds")

The groups all show differences in their means, variance, and distribution shape, with none appearing normally distributed. Each phenology grouping contains one upper outlier outside the 1.5IQR. In particular, the FULL group contains a far outlier (as defined in (Tukey 1977)), sample S54, which is 2.14IQR outside the upper hinge.

Fitting to a linear model and inspecting the variance of the residuals gives:

h1.1.lm <- lm(all_sugars ~ phenology/date_id, data=getAspen())
p1 <- tibble(fitted = fitted(h1.1.lm),
       residual = residuals(h1.1.lm)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=fitted, y=residual)) +
  geom_point() +
  cleangg() +

p2 <- tibble(residual = residuals(h1.1.lm)) %>%

  geom_qq_line() +

p1 + p2 + plot_annotation(title = "Inspection of Assumptions for Linear Model LM1.1",

Group means were calculated without considering date as a random factor (year to year variation excluded). This gives the following result plot with 95% confidence intervals:

Testing for significance, we must first consider homogeneity of variance:

getAspen() %>%
  group_by(phenology) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(all_sugars, na.rm=TRUE), 
            variance = var(all_sugars, na.rm=TRUE))
phenology mean variance
LEAF 9.310586 87.598041

The variances are very unequal, so we select Games-Howell post hoc test which does not require this assumption.

games_howell_test(getAspen(), all_sugars ~ phenology, conf.level = 0.95)
.y. group1 group2 estimate conf.low conf.high p.adj p.adj.signif

Without consideration of inter-annual variation, there is a significant difference in mean sugar content between senescent and non-senescent samples.

Model

Incorporating the date_id as a random factor into a Linear Mixed Model (LMM) to assess the impact of yearly variation:

emmeans((lmer(all_sugars ~ phenology + (1 | date_id:phenology),
              data = getAspen())), ~phenology) %>%
  pairs()

Test of ANOVA Assumptions

To test ANOVA assumptions, we should look at the normality of the residuals of the fitted model:

residuals(h1.1.model) %>% as_tibble() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x="Model Residuals", y=value)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  cleangg()

tibble(phenology = getAspen() %>% filter(!is.na(all_sugars)) %>% pull(phenology),
     residual = residuals(lmer(all_sugars^(0.5) ~ phenology + (1 | date_id:phenology), data = getAspen()))) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_qq(aes(sample=residual)) +
  geom_qq_line(aes(sample=residual)) +
  cleangg() +
  labs(title = "Residuals of Sugars^(1/2) ~ Phenology + (1 | Sampling Date)",
       subtitle = watermark("1.1.2"))

Visualizing QQ Plots of the phenology groupings reveals some large departures from normality, especially in LEAF and SENE:

### Non-Parametric Tests

Assuming we know nothing about the distributions of the different phenology groupings, and due to the violations of assumptions apparent in the ANOVA, can we make observations about the direction of medians between phenology levels?

Kruskal-Wallace Test

getAspen() %>%
  kruskal.test(all_sugars ~ phenology, data = .)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  all_sugars by phenology
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 6.2263, df = 2, p-value = 0.04446

This indicates at least one group differs from the others. Performing a pairwise wilcox test with bonferroni correction:

pairwise.wilcox.test(getAspen()$all_sugars, getAspen()$phenology, p.adjust.method = "bonferroni")
## 
##  Pairwise comparisons using Wilcoxon rank sum exact test 
## 
## data:  getAspen()$all_sugars and getAspen()$phenology 
## 
##      LEAF  FULL 
## FULL 1.000 -    
## SENE 0.208 0.032
## 
## P value adjustment method: bonferroni

Summary of Results

Testing without considering sampling date as a random factor produced significant differences between groups. However, when fitting to a LMM with sampling date as a nested random effect inside phenology, these differences were no longer apparent. Differences between the two years sampled are larger than the differences between phenology states.

To estimate sensitivity to the balance, I repeatedly re-sampled 8 from each group to balance the design and reran the ANOVA:

set.seed(123) # for reproducibility. Removing this line will allow the following code to change pseudo-randomly every time it is run.
getAspen() %>%

Re-sampling this repeatedly doesn’t significantly change the magnitude or p-value. This seems to indicate that the imbalance is not the main driver of the result.

Summary of Results

Starches were generally higher in the when trees were sampled in the senesced state, but variation between years was much higher than between phenology contrasts. The lack of control on this inter-annual variation means that the differences detected between phenology states highly variable and statistically non-significant at p=0.05 when adjusted for multiple tests.

Analysis of H3.1

EDA

S2: Notes

S2.1 Erythritol

Erythritol was excluded from the analysis due to inconsistencies in the units of measurement reported from NRAL, per J.Karst (email).

S2.2 Starch Lab Analytic Method

Due to the analytic method used in starch analysis, content could not actually be distinguished down to glycogen / starch. Therefore, starch values were used and reported as complex carbohydrates with no assumption of molecule origin (fungal/tree)

# load Aspen Datatable
getAspen <- function() {
  df <- readRDS("data/processed/23ARE_datatable.rds")
  return(df)
}

# Get and View Metadata Table
getMetadata <- function() {
  df <- read_csv("data/raw/23ARE_metadata.csv")
  View(df)
}

# Calculate Standard Error
se <- function(vector) {
  vec <- na.omit(vector)
  vec_sd <- sd(vec)
  vec_n <- length(vec)
  se <- vec_sd / sqrt(vec_n)
  return(se)
}

# find_outliers
# creates a binary variable in a supplied dataframe to mark records as outliers
# based off the supplied k parameter where x <> k*IQR(x)

label_outliers <- function(df, var, label_var, k = 1.5) {
  df %>% mutate(outliers = is_outlier({{var}}, coef = k),
                      label = if_else(outliers == TRUE, {{label_var}}, NA))
}

# Count like n() but remove NA
n_na.omit <- function(vector) {
  vec <- na.omit(vector)
  n <- length(vec)
  return(n)
}

# Calculate Confidence Intervals
CI <- function(percentile, n, means, se) {
  p <- percentile/100
  t_value <- qt(1 - (1 - p) / 2, df = n - 1)
  
  col_lower_name <- paste0("lower", p)
  col_upper_name <- paste0("upper", p)
  
  lower_bound <- means - t_value * se
  upper_bound <- means + t_value * se
  
  results <- list(lower_bound, upper_bound)
  names(results) <- c("lower", "upper")
  return(results)
}

# calculate and add mean, n, SE, upper##, lower## columns to a data table, grouped by 
# specified variables and summarized by another variable

mean_n_se_ci <- function(df, group_col, summary_col, alpha) {
  
  p <- 1 - (1 - alpha) / 2
  alpha100 <- alpha * 100
  # create column names
  mean_col <- paste0("mean_", summary_col)
  lower_col <- paste0("lower", alpha100)
  upper_col <- paste0("upper", alpha100)
  
  df %>%
    filter(!is.na(!!sym(summary_col))) %>%
    group_by(!!sym(group_col)) %>%
    summarize(!!mean_col := mean(!!sym(summary_col)),
              mean_n = n(),
              mean_se = se(!!sym(summary_col)),
              !!lower_col := !!sym(mean_col) - qt(p, df = mean_n - 1) * mean_se,
              !!upper_col := !!sym(mean_col) + qt(p, df = mean_n - 1) * mean_se)  %>%
    return()
}

# function for creating a time stamp in to add to a graph for version control
watermark <- function(plotID) {
  now <- format(Sys.time(), format = "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M")
  return(paste0("Plot ", plotID, " Drafted ", now))
}

rm_outlier_3IQR <- function(data, col_name) {
  col_data <- data[[col_name]]
  f_IQR <- IQR(col_data, na.rm=T)
  lower_bound <- quantile(col_data, 0.25, na.rm = TRUE, names=FALSE) - 3 * f_IQR
  upper_bound <- quantile(col_data, 0.75, na.rm = TRUE, names=FALSE) + 3 * f_IQR
  print(paste("Lower Bound: ", lower_bound))
  print(paste("Upper Bound: ", upper_bound))
  
  # Identify the outliers
  outliers <- data %>% 
    filter((!!sym(col_name) < lower_bound | !!sym(col_name) > upper_bound) & !is.na(!!sym(col_name)))
  # Print the outliers
  if (nrow(outliers) > 0) {
    print("These are the rows identified as outliers:")
    outliers <- outliers %>%
      select(1,all_of(col_name))
    print(outliers)
  } else {
    print("No outliers identified.")
  }
  # filter by bounds
  filtered_data <- data %>%
  filter((!!sym(col_name) >= lower_bound & !!sym(col_name) <= upper_bound) | is.na(!!sym(col_name)))
  return(filtered_data)
}

# check design balance

balance <- function(response, pred1, pred2) {
  df <- getAspen() %>% filter(!is.na(.data[[response]]))
  return(table(df[[pred1]], df[[pred2]]))
}

# Q-Q Plots

aspenQQ <- function(response, facet, title, draft_no) {
  ggplot(getAspen(), aes(sample={{response}})) +
  stat_qq() + stat_qq_line() +
  facet_wrap(vars({{facet}})) +
  theme_classic() +
  labs(title = title,
       subtitle = watermark(draft_no)) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust=0.5))
}

# QOL ggplot theme fixes
cleangg <- function() {
  list(
    theme_classic(),
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5),
          plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust=0.5))
  )
}
